<br>
<strong>REFERENCE LIST ENTRY</strong>
<br>
<br>
Add a reference list at the end of your essay citing all sources used in the body of your writing.
<br>
<br>
<strong>Format</strong>
<br>
<blockquote class="ref-hang-indent double-line-spacing">
	Title of article. (Year of publication). <em>Title of Journal, volume</em>(issue), 
	page numbers. DOI (if assigned)
</blockquote>
<br>
For works without a DOI, if the work was accessed from a website (excluding online academic research 
databases, e.g., ProQuest, EBSCO and ScienceDirect) include the URL in the reference. Works accessed 
from an academic database do not require a URL or detail about the database in the reference list. In 
this case, the work would be referenced in the same manner as a print version of the work. URLs and DOIs 
are displayed as a hyperlink.
<br>
<br>
<strong>Example</strong>
<br>
<blockquote class="ref-hang-indent double-line-spacing">
	<span class="hover" title="Title of article">Study smarter, not harder: Setting goals to improve your academic performance</span>. 
	(<span class="hover" title="Year of publication">2017</span>).&nbsp;
	<em><span class="hover" title="Title of Journal">Student Review</span>, 
	<span class="hover" title="volume">25</span></em>(<span class="hover" title="issue">5</span>),  
	<span class="hover" title="page numbers">10&#45;12</span>. 
	<span class="hover fake-aref" title="DOI">https://doi.org/10.12.3456789012</span>
</blockquote>
<br>
If the source displays the DOI number only (e.g., 10.1036/0071393756), convert the DOI into a link 
by adding <span class="fake-aref">https://doi.org/</span> before the number.
