<strong>IN&#45;TEXT CITATION</strong>
<br>
<br>
If you are citing a work which has no author, use the title of the article and year. A shortened title 
may be used if the title is long. Place double quotation marks around the title of an article. The title 
of the article is capitalised using title case (the first letter of each major word is capitalised), even 
though sentence case (the first letter of the first word only, in the main title and subtitle, is 
capitalised) is used in the reference list.
<br>
<blockquote class="in-text-citation">
	&#34;Study Smarter&#34; (2017) outlined the benefits of&hellip;
	<br>
	Alternatively: &hellip;according to a recent study (&#34;Study Smarter&#34;, 2017).
</blockquote>
<br>
If you are using a direct quotation, consisting of fewer than 40 words, enclose the quote using double 
quotation marks and include page numbers.
<br>
<blockquote class="in-text-citation">
	&#34;Study Smarter&#34; (2017) observed that &#34;students are able to improve their 
	performance by&hellip;&#34; (p. 11).
	<br>
	Alternatively: &#34;Students are able to improve their performance by&hellip;&#34; 
	(&#34;Study Smarter&#34;, 2017, p. 11).
</blockquote>
<br>
If the quotation is greater than 40 words, the quote is displayed in a double spaced, indented 
block at 1.27cm from the left margin. Do not use double quotation marks to enclose a block quotation.
